# Storybook for touched or new components

When you **modify** existing React components or **add** new presentational components under `apps/` or `packages/eskerra-ds-*`, decide whether Storybook coverage is needed or useful, and do it **in the same change** (or briefly state why not).

## Do this

- **Design system (L2):** new or changed exports in `packages/eskerra-ds-*` with user-visible behavior or variants: extend stories under `src/__stories__/` or add `*.stories.tsx`. Follow **Storybook contracts** (`.cursor/rules/storybook-contracts.mdc`) — required variants, `play` where required, tags.
- **App UI:** reusable or reasonably isolatable components (shell, panels, lists, form pieces): consider **L3 sandbox** stories (`apps/*/src/**/__sandbox__/*.stories.tsx`, tag `sandbox`) when Storybook isolation helps review; do not add L2 contract stories for full product compositions.
- Update existing stories when props, states, or interactions of the component change.

## Exceptions (no new story required)

- Logic-only changes (hooks, stores, pure utils) with no visual surface.
- Minor styling tweaks without new interaction variants, when existing stories still represent the component.
- Generated or third-party code.

If you skip adding or updating a story, add **one short sentence** in your reply to the user explaining why that is appropriate here.
